  <h2 id="pests">Pest Management Basics</h2>
  
  <p>
  <br>
    Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is the best way to approach pest control in your garden. 
    IPM allows the gardener to look at pests and their role in the garden's ecosystem. 
    By addressing what may attract pests, or environmental factors which can be adjusted to repel them, 
    we are able to effectively protect our gardens while using pesticides as a last resort.
  <br>
  <br>
    <b>Cultural Control</b> of pests means choosing gardening practices that make your plants less vulnerable to pests. 
    This is the most important component of IPM. Some pest like Aphids, mites, and thrips feed by sucking the sap out of a plant's tissues. 
    If your plant is underwatered or overfertilized, the nutrients in these juices will be more concentrated and the plant will be more nutritious to pests.
    By making sure your plants are healthy and properly nurished, but not over-nurished, you can prevent pests.
    Weeding is another form of cultural control. Controlling the weeds in your garden can remove alternate host plants for many of these pests. Your plants will have less competition for water, too, and additional airflow can help prevent fungal growth.
  <br>
  <br>
    <b>Biological Control</b> simply means allowing a pest's natural predators to thrive in your landscape and help you control the pests. 
    Think of your garden as an ecosystem, one with both predators and prey. If you avoid broad-spectrum insecticides, or use them only for severe pest outbreaks, these predators will survive and keep the pests in check in your garden.
    Some bugs that you may first assume are pests may in fact be predatory and protecting your plant. Before you treat, look for damage. 
  <br>
  <br>
    <b>Mechanical Controls</b> are actions, like pruning, that physically remove a plant or pest from the landscape. 
    If you prune away an infested or diseased portion of a plant, be sure to keep it separated from the rest of your landscape plants. 
    Piles of decaying plant material can harbor the pests you hoped to remove.
  <br>
  <br>
    <b>Chemical Controls</b> are important, but a last resort in an IPM approach to pest control. 
    Remember, broad-spectrum insecticides kill beneficial insects along with the pests. 
    IPM recommends beginning with the least toxic products, like horticultural oils and insecticidal soaps, applied directly to the pests.
    Remeber to always use any chemicals only as the label specifies! Deviating from this may cause harm to your garden and local ecosystem. 
  <br>
